  "prompt": "Why do I have black lines on my teeth?",
  "response": "Black lines on teeth can be caused by several factors. Here are some common reasons:\n\n1. **Tartar Buildup**: When plaque hardens on your teeth, it turns into tartar, which can appear as black or brown lines along the gum line.\n\n2. **Cavities**: Tooth decay can cause black or dark spots on the teeth. If not addressed, cavities can progress and become more noticeable.\n\n3. **Stains**: Consuming staining substances like coffee, tea, red wine, or tobacco can lead to discoloration, sometimes appearing as black lines.\n\n4. **Cracks or Fissures**: Small cracks or fissures in the enamel can collect stains, making them appear black.\n\n5. **Dental Work**: Old fillings or dental work can sometimes cause dark lines where the material meets the tooth.\n\n6. **Gum Recession**: As gums recede, the roots of the teeth can become exposed, and these areas are more prone to staining and tartar buildup.\n\nIt's important to consult a dentist to determine the exact cause and get appropriate treatment. They can assess your oral health and provide recommendations to address the issue.",
